Who Cares about Morality

Mariola Paruzel-Czachura, Cillian McHugh

06 February, 2023

H1 Gender Differences

Our first hypothesis was that women would have higher levels of internalization and symbolization than men. To test this we isolated the data for men and women from the main dataset. An independent samples t-test revealed that for the entire sample, women had higher internalization scores (M = 8.0, SD = 1.7), than men (M = 7.5, SD = 1.7), t(46619.03) = -29.94, p < .001, d = 0.28. Similarly, for symbolization, an independent samples t-test revealed that for the entire sample, women had higher scores (M = 5.5, SD = 2.1), than men (M = 5.2, SD = 2.2), t(47135.04) = -14.21, p < .001, d = 0.13.

We conducted a linear-mixed-effects model to test for gender differences in internalization when participants are nested within country. Our outcome measure was internalization and our predictor variable was binary gender (coded as 0 = male; 1 = female); we allowed intercepts to vary by country. Overall, the model significantly predicted internalization, and provided a better fit for the data than the baseline model, \(\chi\)2(1) = 850.40, p < .001. There was a significant main effect for gender, F(1, 47223.29) = 858.06, p < .001; with a significant positive association between being female and higher internalization scores, \(b\) = 0.44, t(47223.29) = 29.29, p < .001. We conducted a series of independent-samples t-tests to test for gender differences in internalization across all countries. We found significant gender differences in internalization across 42 countries. Of these, 40 were in the predicted direction, while in 2 countries (Denmark and New Zealand), males showed higher internalization than females (see Supplementary Materials Table S_X).

We conducted another linear-mixed-effects model to test for gender differences in symbolization when participants are nested within country. Our outcome measure was symbolization and our predictor variable was binary gender (coded as 0 = male; 1 = female); we allowed intercepts to vary by country. Overall, the model significantly predicted symbolization, and provided a better fit for the data than the baseline model, \(\chi\)2(1) = 183.33, p < .001. There was a significant main effect for gender, F(1, 47634.21) = 183.66, p < .001; with a significant positive association between being female and higher symbolization scores, \(b\) = 0.26, t(47634.21) = 13.55, p < .001. We conducted a series of independent-samples t-tests to test for gender differences in symbolization across all countries. We found significant gender differences in symbolization across 24 countries. Of these, 22 were in the predicted direction, while in 2 countries (Taiwan and United States), males showed higher symbolization than females (see Supplementary Materials Table S_X).

H2 Age Differences

Due to mixed findings in the literature, we did not have specific predictions regarding the relationship between age and moral identity, and the analyses reported here are exploratory. Overall there was a significant negative correlation between age and internalization r = -0.022, p = < .001, suggesting that older participants had lower internalization scores. Similarly, we found a significant negative correlation between age and symbolization r = -0.016, p = < .001, again, suggesting that older participants had lower symbolization scores than younger participants.

We conducted a linear-mixed-effects model to test if this relationship between age and internalization holds when participants are nested within country. Our outcome measure was internalization and our predictor variable was age; we allowed intercepts to vary by country. Overall, the model significantly predicted internalization, and provided a better fit for the data than the baseline model, \(\chi\)2(1) = 30.28, p < .001. There was a significant main effect for age, F(1, 47277.86) = 30.31, p < .001; with a significant positive association between age and internalization scores, \(b\) = 0.003, t(47277.86) = 5.51, p < .001. We conducted a series of correlations test if age was related to internalization across all countries. There was a significant correlation between age and internalization in 37 countries. Of these, there was a positive correlation between age and internalization in 11 countries, and a negative correlation in 26 countries (see Supplementary Materials Table S_X).

Similarly, for symbolization, we conducted a linear-mixed-effects model to test if the relationship between age and symbolization holds when participants are nested within country. Our outcome measure was symbolization and our predictor variable was age; we allowed intercepts to vary by country. Overall, the model significantly predicted symbolization, and provided a better fit for the data than the baseline model, \(\chi\)2(1) = 26.14, p < .001. There was a significant main effect for age, F(1, 47672.69) = 26.17, p < .001; with a significant positive association between age and internalization scores, \(b\) = 0.003, t(47672.69) = 5.12, p < .001. We conducted a series of correlations test if age was related to internalization across all countries. There was a significant correlation between age and internalization in 37 countries. Of these, there was a positive correlation between age and internalization in 11 countries, and a negative correlation in 25 countries (see Supplementary Materials Table S_X).
